summaries.title: Developing Leadership Confidence Through Robotics Projects
summaries.summaryText: Ethan described how leading design sprints in the robotics club refined his communication and teamwork skills. He recognized his relative advantage from prior exposure to engineering through his family, and expressed an interest in mentoring peers with less background experience. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Microaggressions and Invisible Labor in Group Dynamics
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Gender Bias and Collaboration
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: First-Generation Challenges in Navigating University Systems
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Representation and Visibility in Engineering Spaces
summaries.summaryText: She emphasized how few Black women were visible in faculty and leadership roles, describing representation as both motivating and emotionally taxing. Her NSBE involvement offered vital affirmation and a platform to advocate for equity. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 1/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 2]
Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 1]
Presented research poster at a regional engineering conference, receiving recognition from faculty mentors. [Timeline 2]
Presented a project on sustainable energy systems at an undergraduate research showcase. [Timeline 4]
Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Intersection of Culture and Academic Identity
themes.description: Cultural expectations of excellence create dual pressure for first-gen students in technical majors. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 4]

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Ethan describing inclusive team leadership philosophy.

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: My parents say, ‘Just do your best,’ but I can tell they really mean, ‘Don’t waste this chance we gave you.’ [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on implicit cultural pressure from family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Ethan on the value of diverse collaboration.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Sarah connecting wellness and academic productivity.

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Aaliyah reflecting on the impact of representation and visibility.

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
